Habitat and distribution:
Breeds in Southern Africa, from S Angola to the W Cape. Location of non-breeding range rather bizarre: a small area in Cameroon and surrounds. Often the only nightjar on dry, open plains in e.g. the Karoo, Kalahari and Namibia but overlaps with Fiery-necked and others where it occurs in sparse woodland. Avoids tropical areas along the E Coast and does not occur in the Lowveld. Often breeds in bare, gravelly or stony clearings.

Status:
Common. Usually singly or in pairs. A breeding summer migrant, arriving in late Aug and departing in Apr-May, but most vocal in spring. A frequent road casualty.

Habitat and distribution:
Widespread across much of sub-Saharan Africa. One of the most common nightjars in Southern Africa, with the exception of the Karoo, Kalahari and arid parts of Namibia (where mostly replaced by Rufous-cheeked). A woodland species that requires thick leaf litter in which to roost and nest. Uses various woodland types, in rocky or flat landscapes, and partly adapted to plantations, parks and gardens too. Forages mostly in clearings, though less prone to sitting on roads than other nightjars. In years of good rainfall, its range expands along wooded drainage lines in dry regions. 

Status:
Common. Usually encountered singly or in pairs, although several singing males can often be heard in a small area. Undertakes poorly understood movements, partly in response to veld conditions. Males tend to return to the same territories year after year, and are often very faithful to their chosen roost sites.

Habitat and distribution:
Distribution centered on the woodland belt of tropical Central and Southern Africa. In our region, mainly in the Lowveld, on the coastal plain and in northern woodlands, but an increasing number of records in fringe areas may suggest a range expansion. Occupies open woodland or scrubby grassland, mainly on low-lying, sandy soils or along river valleys. Roosts in grass or leaf litter at edges of thickets. In KZN and Moz, may be found just above the high-water mark and can be seen flying over the beach in the evening. 

Status:
Common. Movements complex and poorly understood, and may be linked to age and sex. Resident in some areas but migratory in others. A frequent road casualty.

Habitat and distribution:
Occurs in scattered locations across Africa. In our region, restricted to the Caprivi/Okavango region (race carpi) and KZN coastal plain (race natalensis). As its name implies, a bird of moist grassland near water: floodplains, edges of pans, around rivers and lagoons, at wetland margins etc. Prefers thick, short or lightly burnt grassland dotted with taller grass tufts, small plants or Lala palms. In KZN, often in depressions in undulating coastal grasslands and even on the edges of coastal or swamp forest patches. May perch on tracks, posts or shrubs. In SA, has disappeared from some areas of its previous range (e.g. Durban) and now occurs mainly N of the Tugela, and especially in iSimangaliso Wetland Park extending into Mozambique. A small population persists in the Oribi Flats area in S KZN and in the nearby E Cape (e.g. Mkambati NR). Habitat overlaps with Square-tailed.

Status:
Localised and uncommon. Resident, but undertakes local movements in response to fires and water-levels. Singly or in pairs, or occasionally in small groups. Considered Vulnerable in SA, with <1 000 mature individuals occupying approximately 600 km2.
